    <!-- Add Activity -->
     <activity>
        <statement>
            <p><strong>Work in Groups</strong></p>
            <p>
                <alert>Materials Needed:</alert>
            </p>
            <ol><li><p>Drawing board</p></li>
            <li><p>Pen</p></li>
            <li><p>Paper</p></li>
            <li><p>Compass</p></li></ol>
            
            <p>
                <strong>Inquiry Question:</strong> How does the angle of a structural support change when we anchor it at different points along a circular frame?
            </p>
            <p>
                Imagine your group is designing a traditional circular pavilion for a community cultural site. To support the conical roof, you need to run straight wooden beams from a central pillar <m>O</m> to the circular perimeter, as well as spanning beams across the perimeter. 
            </p>
            
            <p><strong>Step-by-Step Practical Investigation:</strong></p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Using a drawing board, paper, and a compass, draw a large circle with center <m>O</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Mark two fixed points, <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, on the lower half of your circumference. The arc <m>AB</m> is your foundation arc.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw radii <m>OA</m> and <m>OB</m>. Use a protractor to measure the central angle <m>\angle AOB</m>. Record this value.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Mark any point <m>P</m> on the major arc <m>AB</m> (on the upper curve of the circle). Draw chords <m>PA</m> and <m>PB</m>. Measure the angle subtended at the circumference, <m>\angle APB</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Move point <m>P</m> to two other positions on the major arc (let's call them <m>Q</m> and <m>R</m>). Measure angles <m>\angle AQB</m> and <m>\angle ARB</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <p><strong>Group Discussion and Recording:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Compare the central angle <m>\angle AOB</m> with the circumference angle <m>\angle APB</m>. What mathematical relationship do you notice between their values?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What did you observe about the values of <m>\angle APB</m>, <m>\angle AQB</m>, and <m>\angle ARB</m> as you moved the point along the same arc? Write down a conjecture based on your measurements.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </statement>
        <figure>
            <caption>A circle illustrating a central angle AOB and a circumference angle APB subtended by the same arc AB.</caption>
            <image>
                <shortdescription>Circle with center O, central angle AOB, and inscribed angle APB on the circumference.</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1]
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (2.5);
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (A) at (-2.165,-1.25);
                        \coordinate (B) at (2.165,-1.25);
                        \coordinate (P) at (0.434,2.462);
                        
                        \draw[red, thick] (O) -- (A);
                        \draw[red, thick] (O) -- (B);
                        \draw[blue, thick] (P) -- (A);
                        \draw[blue, thick] (P) -- (B);
                        
                        \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                        \node[above] at (P) {P};
                        \node[below] at (O) {O};
                        
                        \draw (-0.346,-0.2) arc (210:330:0.4);
                        \node[below] at (0,-0.5) {\small $2x$};
                        \node[below] at (0.434,2.0) {\small $x$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </activity>

