    </axiom>
    <insight>
        <!-- <p>
            <strong>Making Sense of the Geometry: Real-World Visualizations</strong>
        </p> -->
        <p>
            To understand how these circle theorems work, let us connect them to everyday visual ideas:
        </p>
        
        <p>
            <strong>1. Angle at the Centre</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            Imagine holding a giant circular slingshot anchored at two fixed perimeter pegs, <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> (your arc). 
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If you pull the slingshot pocket back to the exact center point <m>O</m>, the elastic forms a wide, open angle (<m>\angle AOB</m>).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If you stretch it all the way back to any point <m>P</m> on the far circular boundary, the elastic becomes tighter and narrower. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Because the boundary point <m>P</m> is much farther away from your pegs than the center, the angle at the circumference is always exactly <strong>half</strong> the size of the angle at the center. Alternatively:
        </p>
        <md>\text{Angle at the Centre} = 2 \times \text{Angle at the Circumference}</md>
        <md>\angle AOB = 2 \times \angle APB</md>

        <p>
            <strong>2.Angles in the Same Segment</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            Imagine points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> represent the left and right sides of a stage in a circular amphitheater. Points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m> are seats at different locations in the balcony.
        </p>
        <p>
            Even though the seats are in different spots (one on the left, one in the middle, and one on the right), every single spectator looks at the exact same width of the stage. As long as you stay on that same curved balcony boundary, your "viewing angle" stays constant!
        </p>
        <md>\angle APB = \angle AQB = \angle ARB</md>

        <p>
            <strong>3. Angle in a Semicircle</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            This is a special case of the Slingshot Rule. If you place your anchors directly opposite each other, the line connecting them is the diameter (<m>RT</m>). 
        </p>
        <p>
            The central angle is now a perfectly flat straight line running through the center <m>O</m>, which measures exactly <m>180^\circ</m>. Since the angle at the edge must be half of the angle at the center, picking any boundary point <m>S</m> and connecting it to the diameter ends will always create a perfect right angle:
        </p>
        <md>\angle RST = \frac{180^\circ}{2} = 90^\circ</md>
    </insight>
    

